The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into negative territory towards the close of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with CEZ shares reached almost half of normal daily business.
The Prague Stock Exchange picked up on Monday's slump at the start of Tuesday trading, when it fell another six percentage points.
This time, the reason for the slump was Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the market's reaction to the outcome of the vote by the US House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilization plan for the country's financial sector, is evident.
Stocks fall in Asia
Stocks in Asian bourses suffered a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indexes recovered some of their losses during the day.
Hong Kong's Hang Seng stock market index lost nearly four percentage points over the course of the business day, but later recovered some of the losses, easing to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five per cent, but then narrowed the losses to 4.3 per cent.
The Taiwan stock exchange fell 3.6 percent after the index there.
"The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, even though it is part of China, determines its own monetary policy, that is, independently of China's central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt the blueprint for supporting the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will also be affected by the slump.
A bloodbath of American shares
The US House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which would cost up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion kƒç).
Lawmakers ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
In Bush's view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis, thereby helping to stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday, with major stock indexes recording their biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly 7 percent, the last time it had a similar drop was in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but as soon as there were signs that the bill would not pass the House of Representatives, the index went into freefall.
Congress makes concession: US government allowed to pump $700 billion into banks
US congressional leaders and President George W. Bush's administration have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
It is due to be voted on early next week.
US lawmakers reached a breakthrough in talks to approve a $700 billion (about 12 trillion kronor) bailout for the US financial system.
However, this does not mean victory yet.
Members of Congress still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be debated in the US Congress on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
The plan could likely not be voted on in the Senate until Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a notification that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor in stimulating financial markets.
After that, however, there is "disillusionment" with the complicated mechanisms for helping the markets in practice.
Paulson: The Plan Must Be Effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our differing views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like, "House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
She said a final vote could come as early as Sunday.
Lawmakers met with Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to finalize the government fund.
This provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets by financial companies, which cause financial firms to incur heavy losses and jeopardise the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must be effective in the market.
We need to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we are on track, "Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada said lawmakers were trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
The move is intended to reassure investors ahead of deals in Asian financial markets, which are in the early days of the year when a decision by Congress could affect business on Monday.
But it is not yet clear when both chambers of the US Congress will vote on the bill, and it is unclear whether the last-minute negotiations might still fail because of a problem.
Lawmakers hope to pass it in the next few days.
The law, however, will undergo some changes.
The total amount allocated to the system will be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush requested.
But Congress can block the distribution of the remaining money if it feels that the program is not performing its function, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush sees positive progress in negotiations
The president has veto power over the decision, but Congress can override its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was based on obtaining finance to buy bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages, has remained intact.
'We've worked it all out.
The House should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday, "said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
American President Bush was also pleased with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and "appreciates the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing perks and setting a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law will also limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establish a committee to oversee the fund.
This is to be run by the Treasury.
"We have worked very hard on this and made great progress toward a deal that works and is important to the market and to all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also includes help for homeowners who are struggling to repay their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on the mortgages it buys, with the goal of lowering the monthly cost to borrowers and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but implementation will be very difficult.
"This is because we do not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be bought up.
That will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government share the losses, "Marek told iHNed.cz. this week.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week does not matter, according to Marek.
"It is much more important that members of Congress agree to support the plan and pass it as quickly as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that it will be adopted is the most important thing at this moment, "Marek stressed.
Duel on a knife edge: MP3 players versus mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls yet.
So, of course, it looks like it's better to buy just one phone.
Nevertheless, there are plenty of reasons why you should buy a stand-alone player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
Sure, it's hard to buy a great expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
For one thing, such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you are probably dreaming of at least one.
This is also the case with music on the move, i.e. with compressed music, put simply - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For some, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand kroner on a player, but equally, a Pink Floyd fan will hardly be able to take headphones off the market for twenty kroner.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide-ranging.
The service life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can play a lot more than just music, but they don't even manage to do what mobile phones can do.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to its primary functions, telephony and sims, it can play music and video, record both, have a better camera and a worse camera, and may also be able to navigate.
And if you include smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle, because no fridge can barbecue and no TV can take pictures.
But the universality of mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to recharge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Only a few mobile phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, in most cases it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
This is why you should expect the cheap mobile phones to be able to play no more than a few hours of music.
If you still make calls from time to time, it is better to buy a charger for the office as a safety measure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the less good ones can withstand at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation with one charge.
Another problem is when you want to transfer the music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB connection, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage device, but only a few card readers can cope with the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With the exception of iPod players, you do not need any special software.
All you need to do is feed the device with music from your PC via USB port.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, ordered by the name of the artist, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating by users.
Some devices only display the tree of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, phones can do more
When selecting a specific device, you should inquire in particular about the service life of the battery, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound and, of course, the ease of use.
If music is primarily a backdrop for you and you only listen to it briefly every day, for example on the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is sufficient.
Which almost every mobile phone can do.
You also don't have to control which music formats a phone or player can handle.
MP3s create all of them, and most of the music you get will just be in this format.
The format is one of the most widely used, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better phones also allow you to buy music online.
All you have to do is access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile internet, and you can then purchase a song or album.
This service can in itself be a powerful argument for why you should buy a music mobile phone.
Unfortunately, the service offered by the providers is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of music sales (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobile phones with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab your phone in your jacket pocket while the player is at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you get a decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones included.
The best and most sophisticated phones with a 3.5mm aperture for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players is the ease of use.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - players can be used by anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the formerly normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable, is obvious.
There is no threat of a collision in the form of an erroneous mobile internet and a subsequent horrendous bill for data transfers.
Which device should you reach for now?
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns will suffice.
But beware.
The basic models usually only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can read 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, then reach for Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
If you are one of the more demanding handsets, take more specialized phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman phones have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players, is the furthest ahead.
The same services in the same price range of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) provide you with MP3 players of the above manufacturers.
The first virtual provider will come to the Czech Republic already this year.

The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classical ones to lower prices.
Perhaps this will not be long in coming.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the ƒåT√ö telecommunications authority, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the European Commission's latest steps in regulating roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition to really challenge.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, given that there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and penetration is well in excess of 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain about the extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo≈ô√°k, President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ƒåT√ö), who has often said in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic, agrees.
It is probably true that a traditional provider with its own network does not have very many chances anymore (by the way, it would probably find hardly any frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which then also the classical mobile telephony providers had to react.
Even before such companies as Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look far for examples.
In February of this year we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, it has managed to attract more than 100,000 customers, making it the fifth largest provider in the country.
The financial group behind Mobilking is Penta, which owns U: fon, among others, in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can concentrate on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
After all, they do not need relatively high costs to build, operate and maintain a mobile network.
In the world, these virtual providers usually present themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but this is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half the price of its rivals.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to target a non-stereotypical audience.
This provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the virtual provider's operator.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that used in Poland could take root in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav ƒåepick√Ω doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of services. "
Opportunity in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"Although we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
It is more likely that mobiles will enter the market in other countries of our region, "Jana Studniƒçkov√°, spokeswoman of the Penta financial group, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to avoid creating a potential competitor.
For some time now, the GTS Novera group has been showing its interest in launching a virtual mobile operator, which would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telef√≥nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a strong interest in offering not only fixed telecommunications services but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in the negotiations, "said the group's spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe better times are coming.
According to unofficial information, the first virtual vendor may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a fully-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has approached us, "says Vlastimil Sr≈°e≈à from the Telef√≥nica O2 press department in his statement for Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also pointed out by other suppliers.
In rare agreement with O2's statement, T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov√° added: "So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further."
She adds: "By the end of the year, hardly any virtual providers will appear on T-Mobile's network.
At this moment we should already have a concrete offer, in order to be able to think in such a short time. "
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav ƒåepick√Ω commented: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
From the customer's point of view, this is precisely what we consider to be the best.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile internet. "
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
It is easy to understand the actions of mobile operators: adding another operator would mean more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus lower profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that providers can pull together when it comes to something is also evidenced by the long back-and-forth over the emergence of U: fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ƒåT√ö came from T-Mobile at the time when U: fon entered the market.
This is also evidenced by publicly available information from ƒåT√ö websites.
But U: fon is a good argument for not allowing a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrov√° commented: "The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services. "
Given this approach by mobile operators, however, the complete lack of interest of Czech regulators is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of ƒåT√ö, which unfortunately - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (√öOHS).
This, however, took its very typical stance on this whole issue.
"The market entry of a mobile virtual operator would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional providers, "says Kristi√°n Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the √öOHS in his answer to our enquiry.
Such a formulation would not come as a surprise to providers' representatives.
From an authority that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position in the market, this is more than questionable.
Especially when Kristi√°n Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators operate as normal, it is noticeable that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephony services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not in the interests of the √öOHS.
What is truly shocking about this case is the almost touching consistency of the three mobile operators in their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely identical price of petrol at petrol stations is surely just a coincidence and the result of fierce competition.
"The Authority has found no indications of anti-competitive behaviour in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The telecoms regulator probably lacks the tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators, "Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of dominance in the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by ƒåT√ö, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - for a virtual provider to enter the market, the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And, logically, the mobile operator has a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you disagree with that argument, it should at least be a warning to the NHS that three mobile phone providers are operating in strikingly similar circumstances.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all providers.
Shifting responsibility to ƒåT√ö is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services by which the √öOHS distances itself from the whole issue.
This has already been observed in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not succeed in extending ƒåT√ö's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, even though a number of experts had hoped it would improve the situation.
The representatives of the √öOHS need to know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one is looking
First of all, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Normally these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company presents itself to the operator as a classic corporate customer ordering a large quantity of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will deal with, which may lead to the termination of cooperation with the respective company," Martina Kemrov√° replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is very unlikely that such a thing will not spread among the leaders of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such an approach.
In fact, they derive not negligible profits from the activities of these companies, and at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav ƒåepick√Ω draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows for this kind of speculation, but in spite of everything, only a very small percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not have their name on it, so they cannot have full access to it like the normal customers of mobile operators. "
That alone, however, should at least seem strange to ƒåT√ö.
There is also a further question for the √öOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such an approach, why are they blocking a virtual provider?
It should be added that the √öOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration by the providers that they do not know about it and that their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been emphasised several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers has led to a significant drop in prices for the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the advanced countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that regulators intervened, not to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal printing, they succeeded in creating the first virtual operator, and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case at themselves like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than favourable in these cases.
But let's not throw the shotgun in the ring.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider emerges soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the emergence of a mobile virtual operator, the √öOHS will not stand idly by when it comes to rejecting (discriminating against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally no longer be making more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
