Prague transport companies will also carry a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, will go down in the history of Prague public transport as the date on which the first passengers to board a metro, tram or bus will carry an electronic coupon instead of a paper ticket.
Currently, about one hundred thousand people with the OpenCard chip card can buy these cards.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day coupon, a 90-day coupon or an annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it applied to their smart card at the same time at the information centres and branch offices of transport companies at the Muzeum, M≈Østek, N√°dra≈æ√≠ Hole≈°ovice, Andƒõl, Roztyly, Let≈àany, Kobylisy, Rajsk√° zahrada, Kaƒçerov and Luka metro stations.
As of yesterday, coupons are also available on the Internet at www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers into the afternoon hours.
Those who use the Internet can really forget the issue window in the subway stations, where they used to regularly have to wait in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, which is then transferred to the OpenCard in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
"Travellers will also have access to a counter with trained staff at these points, which will advise interested parties on internet purchases and also display the coupon on the card," says project spokesman Martin Opatrn√Ω.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be applied to the OpenCard at self-service vending machines installed in some underground vestibules.
What do such vending machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket validators. Passengers may have already noticed them at the underground stations Roztyly, Budƒõjovick√°, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavsk√°.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year it should be eighty," Opatrn√Ω adds.
A vending machine controls the coupon instead of the driver
The operation of the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is simple.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays itself out.
From tomorrow, the electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
In other words, on suburban trains and on bus lines numbered 300 to 499, which mainly serve the inhabitants of municipalities in the Central Bohemia region.
"On trains belonging to Prague Integrated Transport, train attendants have reading devices with which they can check the validity of coupons in terms of time and zone," explains Filip Dr√°pal from the Ropid organisation, which compiles timetables for Prague transport companies.
Suburban buses have card readers at the driver's checkout.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be presented to the driver, but the OpenCard must be placed at a designated location on the side of the cash register.
This enables the driver to check the validity of the coupons uploaded.
