Rats also have feelings
A rat or cockroach flees in case of danger does that mean that it also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
But how could you check if they feel the same if they behave in a similar way to us?
Contributions from famous scientists have been published in the Internet journal "Edge" for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now, when we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it pretends to be dead, escapes or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and execution / control functions).
This wide region is much more highly developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So, at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that humans are different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of human beings: since so much of their experience is linked to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or analyzed on the basis of our own experience because of the special hardware, its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of what I have said refers to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
One could study the processes of consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what is happening in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially visualization.
But this approach, pursued by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, relies more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
So what are the sensations?
I attribute it to the fact that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain that is conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
From this point of view, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and, in particular, humans.
Connected with the linguistic nature there are subtle gradations of feeling, because we can differentiate and categorize states with the help of words and grammar, in order to ascribe them to others as well as ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the bodily emotional regions of the cortex and brain stem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in intergenre sensations.
In purely theoretical terms, I cannot contradict this, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what seems like fear in rats and humans probably feels like fear in both cases: but how can one verify whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees in case of danger if it also feels fear?
