Yet in 2008, an astonishing 100 per cent of fourth-graders passed the state exam at a good level in maths.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth grade were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success has been achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School focuses on verification and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate exceptions.
The school also practices the approach of educating in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should be mindful of, said Principal Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialized instruction.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico. Twelve months later, one would enter the classroom and be unrecognizable.
"It works," she noted, "it works for us."
Would Obama use a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with large percentages of Latino and other English-learning students?
The school's performance would make the answer to that question easy, but education policy positions within his own party (the National Education Associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama's answer uncertain.
While he agrees with the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about "English-only" legislation.
Instead, he said, "you should make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close the achievement gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work, rather than despise and trivialize them.
