The pride and hardships in the lives of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Tucked away among the sprawl of Orlando theme parks, a few miles from the glitzy, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet town where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first all-black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is not as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet the city it describes - and which made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida Guide, produced by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression - is, in many ways, a very special place.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even now, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about race relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We're very attentive to how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, a city resident by birth and a parishioner at the city's oldest church.
It's got to be right. '
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historic example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a literary stronghold and, on the other, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
Unsurprisingly, residents here are both proud and wary.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image really began with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed the city, which is just off Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, into the sites of black history and human drama.
Cheeky as Oscar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"Across the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-and-white painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever-fits-the-hour-room."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
This was certainly not a guidebook.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls that Hurston immortalized, quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual innuendo.
She added: 'Some people didn't like it.'
Hurtson is still remembered here as a feisty eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came to town, she did so mostly without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today has something to do with its venerable attire.
According to Mr Franklin, most residents were intrigued, while many despised her.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Mr Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added, swaying in his chair on a rear terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960 she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary of Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she lived.
In Eatonville, there was no big memorial service, no large-scale public readings.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy in the slightest," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turning point came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to build a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main street of the community.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Compulsory integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"At that time a bunch of white boys would often come and throw oranges and stuff at people sitting on the sidelines," Mr Franklin said.
"There was even once a woman who was killed in the process.
They threw a watermelon out of the car. "
In a 1955 letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's call to force integration, calling its decision in the Brown v. Board case "insulting rather than respectful of my race."
Residents now say that while the repeal of segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened Eatonville's cohesion and the self-esteem of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Protecting the Eatonville Community.
This could be maintained, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"They didn't hug his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped to make room for more Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who defy prejudice, as she did, with positive self-awareness and statements such as: "How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand it. '
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight to revive her fame.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway was on bookshelves, making it part of the American literary canon once again.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the public spotlight.
And this time Hurston's old neighbours saw her as a saviour.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could do with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans turned up for the inaugural event two years later, and many return every January for the celebration.
A few years later, the district abandoned its road plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway enlivened the city, accelerated it at top speed, aroused real civic pride," Ms. Nathiri said.
Ms Boyd put it a little more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
More and more people came, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending church here since 1993, and locals began to reassess the past.
Eatonville was added to the statewide Historic Register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays, Eatonville remains a peculiarity in Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Nowadays it is 90% black.)
Outsiders in search of Eatonville's story and its meaning are often still treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior permission, and certain things - such as the mural of Eatonville's oldest church painted by a white man depicting black men working in the fields - may not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a penchant for dark reds, still worry that their gated community is misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time as the Hurston Festival grew, a heightened degree of homeland pride was born.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better, and just as proud, creative and hard-working, silly and mixed as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city government or the police, who he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think," Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others, "Alondra Kenon said the other day on a Sunday after church.
'But when you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city. '
Here in New York, people are fluent in financial Latin.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and the huge television screens in Times Square, they would not even notice that they were in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass facades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have a monopoly in New York, there is the worst horror day of the day since the stock market crashed in 1929.
Suppliers are still pushing metal tea trolleys along sidewalks with loud clatters, carrying trays loaded with muffins for breakfast meetings.
Latinos still shuffle between apartments, like human pack animals laden with about 50 ironed T-shirts hanging from a yoke-like pole on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for their breakfast bagel at food stalls on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi between 4pm and 7pm on a weekday.
It didn't feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon, when, amid all the doomsday talk, I decided to open a new savings account.
Although I had decided to schedule my mandatory walk on the quiet late afternoon at my JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about 20 people queuing up.
Not at the cash counters to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service counter where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists for directions to the Macy's department store and where new customers open accounts.
Most of them, I later learned from Starr, my "licensed personal bank clerk," were queuing for the same reason I was queuing.
Unlike me, however, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places they commuted from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (a bit like building societies), cooperative banks and those local savings banks that have branches only in one state, and say they treat their customers like family.
Last year, 15 of these banks quietly went bust.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went into receivership, and when New Yorkers drove home over the weekend last Friday, Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion in savings, was looking for a buyer to save.
Fearing another collapse, the clerks and store clerks who lined up before me took their cash to a bank seen as a safe haven, a bank responsible for most of Wall Street's bailout purchases.
Ordinary New Yorkers have been learning fluent financial Latin in recent weeks.
A woman on the phone to my local supermarket in China referred with such familiarity to Lehman Brothers, the failed bank, and its emaciated-looking chief executive Dick Fuld, as if she were railing against a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my block of flats, has strayed from our usual talking points about Brad and Angelina and my food delivery.
