Motorists who can fall behind because of their alcohol levels will have to install the 'Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who has had three official penalties for drink driving, install this system in his car, which forbids him to start the car when drunk. If he is drunk, the car does not start.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the Attorney General's report, which she says is a pilot project that will last a year.
The purpose is to resocialize the driver, which is why he gets a course in re-education of traffic behavior.
In addition to the General Prosecutor's Office, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute of Automobile Safety will also participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of motorists who were reported more than once for driving under the influence of alcohol put themselves back behind the wheel.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents car start if the driver has taken a breathalyzer test; or if an alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than permitted.
It costs more than EUR 1 000 and the costs are borne by the person who imposes the sanction.
In this context, a study conducted in the USA in 2007 has shown that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of rule violations in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate its implementation, a legal reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the Basic Law, which is necessary for the prosecution process, is called for.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish markets, in any store, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
Tomorrow, of all days, the Chamber of Deputies will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
