Conversation - The Blood That Became Safe Again
Yesterday, Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its President, Dr Francine D√©cary, had every reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
Above all, it has regained public confidence, badly shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980 "s and 1990" s.
It is known that the national blood reserves administered by the Blood Service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with HIV and hepatitis C during the 1980s.
Faced with this tragedy and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, with the aim of shedding light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to draw up guidelines to prevent another disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever hesitated to issue his report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for managing blood stocks in Canada.
In Quebec, the G√©lineau Committee carried out this task.
According to reports by G√©lineau and Krever, two blood banks have been established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
'In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started its work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood collection system in Quebec, 'remembers Dr D√©cary.
The situation was dispiriting.
Through enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood vessels, and through work in this field over the following years, we have regained the public's trust, 'she says, before proudly pointing out that by early 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
But Dr D√©cary keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has followed the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed the emergence in Europe of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
'And we didn't have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we invoked one of the main guidelines of the Krever and G√©lineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied when we do not know and when a disease progresses slowly, as is evidently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself in brain degeneration, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago it was proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the precautionary principle that we have applied does make sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, rather than the antibodies to the virus, as was the case with the tests used to date.
NST has made it possible to shorten the incubation period between the time the person is infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood using our techniques, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it and without being able to detect it.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
'In other words, you'd have to distribute 12 million blood samples before anyone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood sample.
I believe that nowadays you can feel good when you get or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health, 'says the director of Hema-Quebec.
'Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen can get into the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of R√©union, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
We must monitor continuously, 'continues Dr D√©cary, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide sufficient care in addition to secure care.
'Demand is rising because the population's ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population is also having an impact on the blood donor network, which, on average, includes only 3% of Quebec's eligible population. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who make their blood available are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and anyone who has travelled to a country where malaria is prevalent is excluded from giving blood for one year.
'With this 3%, we're able to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and are unable to donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep it and to get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour giving blood, 'Francine D√©cary laments.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec's only public umbilical cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, once considered biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukaemia.
'A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we're planning to take more than a thousand each year.
'We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year, 'explains Dr D√©cary, who describes the umbilical cord blood collection programme as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced they don't have access to it 'because Hema-Quebec lacks the resources to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
