Many voters believe they will find salvation in a party that preaches virtue, law and order, but they do not see that this government has renounced what has been the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, Mr Toews, lies in that slogan, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy General Manager of the Canadian gold mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, using Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company was seeking a six million libel action against three authors and a small penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening up a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of libel actions, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to engage in public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to express an opinion contrary to theirs.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of the Book of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the near-inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
Moreover, the tactic of these unequal struggles is often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the opposing side and also discourages anyone who dares to revisit the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view before public opinion.
Contrary to what is commonplace in many of the countries in which Barrick Gold operates, in Canada debates are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas, not through blows.
So it would have sufficed if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened up a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent audit teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no faith in public opinion, brushing aside petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a wave of the hand.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how, at the same time, he can ask for a 'public' debate and yet disregard the opinions of that very public?
Apparently, in the world of the vice president, that word only encompasses generously paid lawyers, not the community of all Canadians; a pretty narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public, which supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, does so largely because it rejects the gold mine's brutal stance.
This public is willing to listen and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in what many perceive as a gag suit (in the course of the 'public debate', Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, asking them to stop using the term...).
Aside from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's lawsuit is a direct attack on academic freedom and truth-telling, which are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss the facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to research and debate issues that the world's rich companies do not like, who else can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could conduct it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no appetite for transparent debate.
This is a loss to the university world, as well as to public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to curb this type of unwarranted complaint.
Wall Street bailout - Democrats and Republicans get along
The Bush administration and senior members of Congress, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, designed to stop the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months, has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
The main contents are: better control of MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money used, new provisions to limit the number of houses seized due to arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
The US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
'We have made great strides toward an agreement that will be effective in the marketplace, 'Bush administration official Henry Paulson said.
'It was all done to protect the real economy and the American people from the crisis on Wall Street, 'the Democrat said.
'This is the fundamental point: If we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and turmoil in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous, 'Republican Judd Gregg said.
Negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, fearing the effect that another failure would have on investor sentiment.
The deadline agreed was the opening of the market this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who entered the negotiations late, were more in favour of the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to hit them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted that certain executive orders be added to the settlement, especially those that would allow owners to keep their homes and those that affect the salaries of the executives of the companies rescued by the state.
'When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, it's not something you can congratulate yourself on.
But these measures are necessary, 'he said on US television.
When asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: 'I'd like to know the details first, but I hope so.
'The guidelines I've read [show] that this is something we're all going to have to digest and move forward with.
The option of doing nothing at all is simply not acceptable, 'he said.
The $700 billion plan is aimed at using taxpayers' money
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky subprime mortgages, before spreading to other forms of more widespread bonds (PCAAs), and finally to a freeze in financial strength and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican lawmakers who failed the first attempt at a deal last week.
Ever since Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of distressed companies should be secured only by the government, not bought, they believe they have escaped the impasse.
To round things off for everyone in Congress, an executive order was added stating that if the government made a loss on the program within five years, it could then levy new taxes to get its capital back.
The new plan calls for the payment of an initial sum of $250 billion, to which a further $100 billion could be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion must be approved by Congress in another vote.
In return for its help, Washington gets shares in the companies it supports, which it pays dividends on profits, and which it can sell again when the storm passes.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to halt the attachment proceedings concerning the homes linked to the real estate loans affected by this plan, and also to set deadlines for repayment and severance payments to the executives of the companies concerned.
Developers of the plan would like the House of Representatives to vote on it as early as today, and the Senate to vote on it on Wednesday.
Despite their best efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
Indeed, there were more voices against the plan yesterday, from both Republicans and Democrats.
'Obviously, Washington doesn't understand us, 'Republican Scott Garett, a member of the chamber's Finance Committee, told voters.
'Yes, we've got a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But it's not the one that's going to make taxpayers pay. '
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, who heads a group in Congress called the "Caucus of Skeptics," puts things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
'Four hundred distinguished economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us that we are asking Congress not to be pressured and to think carefully about which way to go, 'he said yesterday.
At the same time, we in Europe have once again seen proof that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg came after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy out its competitor, which has been in deep trouble since losing 2 billion euros (2.9 billion dollars) in the crisis due to high-risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
'This is not lost money, 'Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, we are given the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households value now that uncertain times are looming. '
During this period, on the other side of the Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalizing another bank that had been troubled by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans from Bank Bradford and Bringley, including more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) from real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the UK bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to be nationalised by the UK government since the start of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (19252008) - Death of a committed icon
His beauty with azure eyes has long been his trump card, no one would say his weakness.
Had the American actor freed himself from the narcissistic mirror with his charming smile?
Yes and no.
His sensitivity, sensitivity and obvious talent have probably also kept him away from a position of power that gives birth to the truly terrible monsters.
But what a great runner!
Paul Newman, who died on Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer at his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema in his golden years.
He was less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled and for whom he had long been a kind of on-screen rival, more meticulous in his acting, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and breaking dramaturgical conventions.
Mixed blood often makes wonderful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German Jew and a Hungarian mother.
From his European roots came one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, ultimate quality feature.
For it reflected a whole country that was in love with the self-made man, the fighter who was wounded in battle in the Pacific War, who studied acting at Yale in the early 1950s and then visited the Actor's Studio in New York before finding success in the theatre, on television and soon in the cinema.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also the driver who finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Mans, and also a sex symbol, despite having lived in a model relationship with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him disappear also the unknown facets of this mysterious, reserved, committed and over-sensitive to the glamour of showbusiness, the riddle of which will never be completely solved.
A decent man, in the purest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman sent cinema-goers into a frenzy this weekend as all his major roles were played out on the dark screen of memories.
More than half a century of American cinema in constant change passes with him.
The charming cowboy from "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid" (1969) comes to mind again, as does the young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Hot Tin Roof, which was made into a film by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
A much more recent memory (1990) is awakened, that of his sensitive Mr. Bridge, who in his old age is disturbed by a wedding that did not fulfill all its promises.
There have been so many other Paul Newmans throughout history.
This criminal, boisterous, violent and unforgettable boxer Rocky Graziano from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role that was meant for James Dean but was revived after his death and made Newman a household name in 1956.
This likeable crook in the outstanding The Sting (The Clou), which won the Oscar for best film in 1973.
As an embittered and vindictive billiard player in the wonderful The Hustler by Robert Rossen (1961),
That face through the ages, that was him.
Still him.
His CV combines epochs.
Young people know him primarily from the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, the unorthodox coach of an ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy by the Coen brothers.
A final role in 2003 as the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Sam Mendes's Road to Perdition came full circle.
In contrast to several cinema legends who retired from the film world early enough, Newman should stay in the saddle for a long time, betraying Hollywood, his fortune, his pomp and his concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier saw him, not without humour, as a living challenge to 'underplaying' as he judged his over-expressive performances.
The profession has not always been easy for the beautiful Paul Newman, who for a long time found the roles so alluring.
But he rarely played Sunnyboys as outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, naysayers or the desperate, whose perfect portrayal reflected his slide and rebellion.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown sides of his true sensitivity.
His Rachel, Rachel from 1968 (based on the novel by the Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, painted a subtle portrait of a woman full of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son to him, a work full of sensitivity and sadness.
Amid the deluge of tributes pouring in for Newman yesterday, his close friend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had starred together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) made a poignant statement: 'His presence has improved my life and this country.'
Generosity and zest for life were essential traits of the late actor.
Aside from his legendary career, there is now a great champion of civil rights, environmental protection and independent cinema, an opponent of Hollywood's drift.
We have probably often seen him standing with his foot in bowls full of vinaigrette, in sauces, pastries or other foods, and thought this was rather tasteless, although we thought it was funny at first.
Profits from his sales, however, went to his Children in Need foundation.
Instead of resting on his laurels, Newman committed himself to the shot.
He left a letter to his five daughters saying: 'Always and until the very end your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
It's been an honour to be here. '
And it was an honor for us to follow the life of such an intelligent and generous American actor.
An exemplary citizen, in the narrowest and broadest sense.
