The psychology of outbidding - or why we're willing to pay more
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue what is being offered.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even inflated prices.
The researchers tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was asked to play the lottery while the other participated in a playful activity - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cortex, was measured in auction losers, where outbidding of the opponent plays a major role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To back up their thesis, the economists in the Research Unit have also conducted research on tracking money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward if they emerged victorious.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost if the game was lost.
The only difference between the two groups was that the emphasis in one group was on winning and the other on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypotheses expressed by neurologists, the members of the "anti-losing" group were willing to bet higher than those in the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have justified the behaviour observed at auctions so far only with the joy of winning, or rather the avoidance of risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to neurological imaging techniques, so we now have a third explanation, "said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should I see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - hepatitis and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in the case of hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), and in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other bodily fluids (such as semen, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travellers are advised to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, but there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
Jaundice then appears on the skin and eyes, stool becomes light, urine darkens, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, around 1 million people die each year from the far more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people infected is on medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen treacherously destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is therefore essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C sufferers worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
As the disease can already be detected during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your GP at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognised in good time, the disease can be cured and the virus can be eradicated, thereby reducing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first held in 2004 by patient advocacy groups around the world.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, its emergence and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
Recent research shows that religious faith acts as a kind of "painkiller," which is said to have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment to investigate the extent to which belief in God influences people's perception of pain, reported the British newspaper "Telegraph."
In the more bizarre investigation, 12 believers and one atheist each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
A brain scan technology has even shown that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project involving not only scientists but also philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
During the experiment, the subjects were tied to a sparkling device on their left hand, which delivered the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: a painting of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Ermine."
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's painting because it was little different from the other painting and was perceived as reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were asked to look at either the religious or the other painting.
Catholics reported feeling "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "cared for," and they felt "peace and quiet."
While viewing the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo's work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be produced with other strong-looking images in atheists, one just had to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find an image that elicits very positive sensations, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practising the faith should change our personality, and it does in many cases," Wright said.
After these excellent results, the only question that remains is what effect a Madonna painting by Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the regulation of the pain of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the occasion of its tenth birthday, Google has every right to say that it is in people's pockets as well as above their heads in the sky: it knows where people have spent their holidays, which specialists they go to, and what moves them.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of Google's chief executives.
In the direction of sceptics who are plagued by Orwellian horror visions, he points out that these would overlook the very essence of Web 2.0.
In a recent interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt said that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal information about users, moving closer to the company's original goal of "ordering all the information in the world."
Schmidt said that after ten years of world-changing work, Google is still only at the beginning of information gathering.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google would be able to answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "Which job really suits me?," but software programs are not yet able to do so because they don't know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches, the search terms would be registered, as well as the IP addresses from which they searched, and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search," introduced two years ago, allows visitors to save their own search history and access it later, so that the results can be generated much more precisely later, and the so-called "recommendations," with which the system recommends tailor-made products and services based on previous preferences, are based on the same logic.
However, users wonder what happens in the event of data misuse - "If you look at what I do" - and some are concerned about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is the potential power represented by the company that is scary, rather than the sense of guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or the revolt against power, that is rejected by many Internet users.
However, it is a proven fact that search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties on occasion, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent action against paedophilia in Brazil, in which Google handed over to the Brazilian Government information collected by the Community site called 'Orkut', which also made it possible to identify paedophilia.
However, users concerned about their personal rights were able to breathe a sigh of relief in May, when Google, together with the civil rights organization EFF, successfully took the FBI to court: according to this, Google cannot be forced under any section of the Constitution to hand over information to the FBI on a secret request.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago; however, the list of individual users, respectively their web and search terms list, has been withheld from it for two months retroactively.)
So Google's image remains controversial: those who are reluctant to disclose their personal data because they fear the loss of their privacy and intimacy by using Google's services are castigating the company with the indignation that befits conservative companies.
Meanwhile, the American "geek culture," which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists, and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which, thanks to Windows, is the market leader, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require identification codes from its users and makes its services available free of charge, so that an open, constantly updated source code and program package seem far more attractive, youthful, and cool than the software giant's official practices.
On the other hand, geeks are razor-sharp in understanding the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet - a relationship that has come to the fore in recent years, especially thanks to the term "Web 2.0."
"Web 2.0" is all about collaboration, in other words, the users intentionally leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions vary from individual to individual, the main thing remains the same, namely to show up publicly.
The average young person can manage their profiles simultaneously on multiple community portals - from Facebook to Xanga, can connect them using other services, such as Twitter, or music services, such as last.fm, and can eventually integrate all of this into a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. They can also maintain blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries posted on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove this: when looking at the party photos from the previous night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful boyfriend has been having fun with, or the employee is fired because he honestly vents his anger about the company's management on his blog - one thing is certain: the term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Who leads an online life is what he or she reveals about himself or herself - something like this could be the basic idea behind the behaviour of today's youth.
And anyone who tries to keep something secret, or even circumvent Google's monopoly, is welcome to do so - for example, with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine but deliberately leaves no trace.
Quite a few people deliberately do not register on community sites so that they cannot be found, but Google's online applications, such as word processing and graphical tools and RSS feeds, can also be circumvented with alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible user profile.
Public opinion, meanwhile, is anxiously waiting for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), AdWords / AdSense's advertising space is threatening advertising agencies "revenues, and the increasingly rapid introduction of services is a headache not only for Microsoft, but also for other software developers.
Critics, however, also find the troubling counter-poles: for example, the company's management rejected an employee protest after the company's kindergarten fees were doubled, and management said that multiple meals for employees were too expensive. However, all this seems positively mild compared to the fact that Google even bowed to the Chinese government in 2006 and agreed to an agreement that all dissident hits, or those that violate good taste, would be filtered out.
The company's internal policy is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only when it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could turn things around: While some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project is now assuming proportions, that the company will soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, others are more concerned about the "Health" system, which enables the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database is already providing the stuff for the next generation of sci-fi writers - for example, "Scroogled," Cory Doctorow's famous novel describes, in the best Orwellian style, a future in which a human being becomes frighteningly approachable thanks to Google-sourced data.
