Intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if not to imitate obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, bees.
An amazing project was presented at CEATEC in Japan, where Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees to create new accident-avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by automobile robots, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area," which is very similar to our own "shield," said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance measurement.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is registered in a fraction of a second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees, rotating the tires at the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this manoeuvre takes place purely instinctively.
"If it were not, the automobile robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the automobile robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, because this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a split second.
However, unlike the bees, the swerving cannot be up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the manoeuvrability of the tyres.
While the bees here have an infinite number of possibilities to evade other bees, the researchers were only able to use rotary motion, respectively acceleration and deceleration, in the automobile robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly.
It doesn't need to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so it only needs a handful of KB of memory all the time.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of instant collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in mass production within the next ten years.
The technology could also be used in GPS satellite navigation, by consciously steering drivers around obstacles and thus guiding them to their destination.
