Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which, in a report circulated today in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on Current and Recently Identified Health Risks) of the EU.
"It is clear from the report that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for more than an hour a day for at least five years risk permanent loss of hearing."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people, who usually turn portable music devices and mobile phones to a high volume, are irretrievably damaging their hearing without knowing it," said Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific evidence," the EU said, "shows a clear risk and urges swift action.
What really matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information a common good.
In the light of this scientific evidence, we need to re-examine existing control systems to ensure they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology. "
Brussels had asked the independent scientific committee to investigate the widespread use of portable music devices among young people.
"The EU Communication concludes that there is legitimate concern and that the European Commission, together with the other EU Members and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music devices and similar devices."
There is already a European standard that limits the level of noise from portable music devices to 100 dB, and there is concern about the damage that too much noise could cause.
This damage can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and the length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the Scientific Committee of the European Union points out that if the users of portable music devices listen to loud music for only five hours a week (louder than 89 decibels), the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at work are already exceeded.
Those who exceed this limit risk complete loss of hearing within five years.
This would therefore affect 5-10% of users of such devices, which can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
