The elite is in danger
The phenomenon was revealed a few days ago, when the House of Representatives voted against the White House's $700 billion austerity package: a large portion of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's edition of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis is gradually dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly split into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and the business community, and the neoconservative party, which is hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, and which wins voters, especially in the South and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise primarily to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example I have just mentioned, however, is only a small part of the great changes that the current economic earthquake is heralding or is already heralding: not only in the United States, but also in the whole of the West and perhaps beyond, will be affected by them.
Both in the States and in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means the demise of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and, at the same time, manage an enormous amount of the wealth of households residing in a single state.
This poses an immediate political problem for governments: how to deal with the families affected, who are also a huge number of voters.
The crisis thus appears to be global in economic terms, while it is almost purely national in political terms.
Political internationalism seems to have thus been sidelined and lost its right to speak: the obvious proof of this has been provided by the EU, which, due to its dichotomy into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone is now counting on the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and above all the distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the US is able to save itself economically without foreign help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two preconditions that cannot be overestimated - under certain circumstances - that no international organization and no market will otherwise be able to fall back on in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the state-national element is, moreover, perfectly in line with the ever-increasing importance recently attached to an intimately related sector in the economy: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked global empire, a realm of increasingly differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we suddenly have to realize how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to another in the world, but they are nevertheless extremely connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth - a territory.
Therefore, one who has such a territory has an advantage over another who lives in an area without crops, without water or without oil.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short insertion.
Who says territory, who says government, who says politics, means leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to be generating two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to manage things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation against the existing leaderships, especially those of economics, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadowy areas.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a certain sense, even more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of impracticality, a sense of distance, all directed at an entire class of Western managers.
There seems to be a conviction among large sections of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, the content of which is becoming increasingly foreign and outdated to the majority.
The demand for leadership, then, is feeding an underground ramified but powerful movement for the disempowerment of the ruling class and the traditional political establishment, manifested in unforeseen "revolts" by voters and in the sudden reversal of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, through the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of American lawmakers against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual believers, some would say their format, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value with regard to what is happening in the lower social strata of the West today, which is being intensified and driven to the point of superdimension by the financial crisis.
In view of all this, it would be simply an exaggeration to speak of a "mass rebellion."
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not the answer.
