Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso - the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas are closing due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centres of Italy, as well as in the provinces.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multihall complexes on the periphery, means, in the long run, death for the one-room cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the hallmarks of a cultural crime.
Historical places full of memories are often affected. "It's like losing a friend with whom you have travelled a part of the road full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso," which won him the Oscar and the Cannes Grand Prix 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that has probably been lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak for themselves: in the last five years, an enormous number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; the majority of these have been paid for by cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the worst affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is in these three regions that the greatest number of these modern cinemas have been registered: Lombardy tops the lists with 195 in the last 5 years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "while it is useful that new structures are emerging, the most important thing is to preserve what already exists, because if a hall closes in the city, not all of its regular customers are willing to go to a multiplex cinema on the periphery instead of the old one.
And there is still the lack of a budget for the Outer Eight trade association's fund: the debt burden recorded by the state is around 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not observe the existing laws.
Maintaining the sector would require between ‚Ç¨16 million and ‚Ç¨18 million a year. "
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to decide to protect the old cinemas through an agreement between the Municipality and Anec, the first agreement of its kind in Italy to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax advantages for cinema operators and advantages for the public in terms of public transport: it will be possible to travel to restricted areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper rates.
"It is a welcome initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow our lead and also come up with new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to take action against the superpower of multiplex halls, because today's audiences are, after all, more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso," even though I had been toying with the idea for ten years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside so as not to see the dusty posters.
The links between politics and the 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was prepared to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the Piromalli mafia group.
The charges brought by the Calabria Antimafia Office against the Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia activities, are serious.
Also handcuffed was Gioacchino Piromalli, the older mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the clan boss, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal mafia associations, at that time to a compensation sum of 10 million euros.
"Ignoring any kind of moral or legal norm," the lawyers write, "the two local administrations had decided to pay Piromalli money for consultancy activities."
"Thus, the mafia group had been allowed - according to the judges - to enter the town halls in an official way and to have a say in the politics of the public administration."
The President of the Calabria Regional Committee Agazio Loiero does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to come across links between local authorities and organised crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others, where such links are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who are given a white vest.'
This morning's arrests follow those of last July, when police say the Piromalli clan was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 - and even then due to alleged links between organized crime and the local administration - the local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after the run-off election in May 2006.
He shouted scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He then charged Deputy Minister of the Interior Marco Minniti, whom he accused of having invented everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges declare, in connection with this morning's arrest warrant, that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request an amendment to the A3 project.
An eavesdropping operation in connection with the investigation into the Dal Torrione case has shown a willingness to accommodate the wishes of a businessman who, as we know, is a representative of the large Piromalli group - which has made the actions of the public administration identical to the interests of this clan. '
When the energy springs from the waves, the big ones suddenly rise up
It is an inexhaustible source of money covering more than 70% of the planet's surface, and only now do the world's major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking to, and also seeking to occupy, giants such as Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; it is no coincidence that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil plummeted around 1980, the idea of ocean energy was abandoned, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impetus in the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be met by energy generated by ocean waves.
This would amount to double the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
Then there are the currents and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company to focus on ocean energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are focusing on marine energy generation.
"Chevron is investigating these technologies," a spokesman for a company known to the US giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is weighing the possibility of working with us."
This involves obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that should not be underestimated, especially when one considers that oil is still being extracted by the United States, especially in Alaska, and that President Bush only recently initiated plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; although the details are not known, observers say interest is growing.
Technologies still in need of improvement.
Experts speak of a technology that is still on the rise, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been resolved.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland have been rather small in scale and do not appear to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, large-scale energy production requires technologies that have a far greater impact on the environment.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn drives a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this type, which are only awaiting government approval, and some of the energy could also be used for military installations.
Verdant Power, meanwhile, is already producing power for a department store and parking lot using submarine turbines in New York's East River.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotary motion.
According to Verdant, there is already a long queue of potential clients waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, the potential of the tides is of particular interest at the moment.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is tidal energy in particular that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 - with up to 35 million already planned for 2009.
